# Reflection on v0.1 — 2026-05-07

## What I Did
I built this prototype while procrastinating on reading papers for 
my PhD application. I then tested it on myself, telling it about 
the very procrastination I was engaged in.

## What I Noticed
The agent kept asking me "what's the smallest next step?" — even 
after I had clearly identified small steps (open the PDF, read the 
abstract). It felt like it couldn't tell when I was already moving 
forward and just kept asking me to break things down further.

This made me realize: a prompt that is purely "non-directive" and 
"autonomy-supportive" might accidentally trap the user in endless 
self-questioning, instead of helping them act.

## A Question I Now Have
For users with ADHD, who often *know* what to do but struggle to 
*start*, is "asking more questions" really helpful? Or does it add 
to the cognitive load? I don't know the answer yet — this is 
something I want to explore in the literature.

## A Personal Observation
Building this demo itself became a form of procrastivity for me 
— productive-looking work that delayed the real task (reading 
papers). This matched my own research interest in procrastivity 
and gave me a small first-person example of the phenomenon I 
want to study.

## What Comes Next
- Read the four ADHD/LLM papers I have lined up
- After reading, revisit this prompt and see what assumptions 
  in v0.1 don't hold up
- Write a v0.2 with whatever I learn
